    On the dark and dreary afternoon of February
23, Dean Hoelscher, at the request of the
Engineering Student Cabinet had a rap session with
the student body in the nearly completed Benedum
Hall Auditorium. Of the student body of 1600, only
27 students showed up. Those who did show up had
many   questions and   gripes to throw  Dean
Hoelscher's way. He was kept busy for two hours
answering them. The following is a rough ap-
proximation of the discussion.


Q. How can a group get the use of Benedum Hall
Auditorium?
A. Make the request through your department or
the Engineering Student Government. The
auditorium is to be used as a meeting place for
groups of engineers. It will not be used as a class
room for ES or any other courses.


10


Q. Engineering students attending Pitt's Johnstown
extension campus were told that the two year
curriculum at Johnstown would enable them to come
to Pitt as full-fledged Juniors, even in credit with
students who attended Pitt's Oakland Campus for
their Freshman and Sophomore years. When they
got here, they were told they were four credits short
because their core humanities and Social Science
courses were three credit hours rather than
Oakland's four credit hour core courses. We've gone
to everyone we could see and action is still pending
but we don't even know where it is pending.
A. Dean Hoelscher said that he was aware of the
problem. He and Dean Turkes meet every morning
to discuss problems in undergraduate engineering.
Students should realize that the various departments
are relatively autonomous in determining what is
acceptable for a degree; each department will have
to make its own decision. Dean Hoelscher said that it
sounds like the students have a legitimate gripe, that
they're short credits through no fault of their own
and he hopes they get a fair resolution of the
problem. Dean Turkes said that he would help to
expedite the resolution of the problem.

  Q. I took a humanities elective with the OK of
my advisor and now they tell me it isn't applicable
toward my degree. Why can't a list be distributed to
the students of acceptable electives? My advisor
didn't know the course wasn't acceptable.


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER_WINTER, 1971



A. Elective acceptability is determined by each
department and the list is given to the advisors. An
advisor has no excuse for not knowing what courses
are acceptable. An advisor is an official represen-
tative of a department and if he signs your schedule,
then the courses on your schedule have been ac-
cepted as creditable toward your degree. If you have
any trouble this way then come see me. I'll see if it is
possible to get a list of acceptable electives
distributed to the students.



