  Q. Why aren't there more blacks in the School of
Engineering and are we doing anything to get more
in?
A. Dean Hoelscher said that only 2 per cent of
engineers are black. We are operating on a number
of fronts to correct this situation. We provide ex-
change faculty with a number of primarily black
universities. Many of Pittsburgh city high school
graduates don't have the math background for
engineering. Those black students who do come out
of Pittsburgh   high schools with  good  math
backgrounds are highly sought after by many
Universities. We don't get many. We started a
program about four years ago which would give
twenty-two black high school graduates who didn't
have sufficient math background remedial courses
and let them start their Freshman year later. Half
way through the first semester, they and their in-
structors, came to me wanting to be entered into the


regular Freshman program. I agreed but only about 4
managed to graduate. We are starting a new program
with a three term freshman year and this time I will
not agree to let them switch programs. I hope we get
better results in this way.


Q. Our Nation      is reevaluating  its priorities,
Education, in general, is doing the same. What is the
Engineering School doing to reevaluate its priorities
and to help improve our society?
A. "A couple of hours wouldn't be enough to
completely cover that subject," stated the Dean.
"Engineers are trained to solve problems in the real
world and our real world is changing rapidly. The
most rapidly changing part of the real world is
priorities. The curriculum must change with these
priorities. Pitt's School of Engineering is a leader in
this curriculum change. Recently we. have started
three specialties: Environmental Engineering, Bio-
Engineering and an Energy resources development
and management department."














