Q. You said nothing in your definition of an
Engineering education about providing the student
with an intellectual experience which will carry on
into and enrich the rest of his life.
A. Well, that should have been presupposed in
what I said.


Q. If Pitt's School of Engineering can't accept
many of the Pittsburgh high school black graduates
because their schools give them  poor math
background, why doesn't the school lessen the rigor
of its curriculum so it can accept more Pittsburgh
graduates and better serve the city it receives free
services from? Could not Pitt institute a less rigorous
engineering technology course?
A. No. If we turn out a Civil Engineer, he has to be
able to build a safe bridge or building. The same is
true with the other departments. A certain com-
petence must be maintained. We are starting a less
theoretical and mathematical curriculum on the
Johnstown campus. It has more emphasis on english
comprehension, communication and applied
engineering. It is a course equal in quality but dif-
ferent in kind with the programs on the Oakland
campus.


Q. Many people in industry and in the academic
community say that engineers are weak in writing
skills. Don't you think more English and Humanities
should be included in the engineering curriculum?
A. History majors can't write. Soc. majors can't
write. Chemistry majors can't write. I don't think
most college graduates can put together a syn-
tactically correct sentence. Don't just hang the label
on engineers. A major problem in education is how
to put together an effective and interesting course
with 300 students at a time. The idyllic situation
would be to have a one to one corespondence, one
Professor to  one student, but that is not
economically feasible. Engineering education has
the particular problem of what can be left out. There
is so much that should go into a four year course that
it's hard to decide what is necessary and what will
have to be left out. We had a five year engineering
course but five year grads did not receive em-
ployment advantage over four year graduates so the
program was dropped.


