Q. When the money is divided between schools,
how does the Engineering School rate in order of
priorities?
A. Priorities run in cycles at Pitt. A long time ago
the University of Pittsburgh decided it wanted a top
medical school so it put a lot of money into it and
they have a top medical school. Later, Pitt wanted a
top Philosophy department. The money flowed and
the Philosophy School is now rated fourth in the
nation. In 1965, when I was made Dean of the School
of Engineering, I was charged with the task of
making Pitt's Engineering School one of the best in
the nation. Since then we've acquired Benedum Hall,
a fifteen million dollar building and five million
dollars of new equipment to go into it. In the five
years since I took over, out budget has tripled but
the student body has not increased significantly. The
emphasis has been on quality.

























