     Education   is a  very  exciting  endeavor.
 Classroom teaching and out of class interaction with
 students does provide me with some of my most
 satisfying university experiences. To watch an in-
 dividual student grow in knowledge and skills as he
 or she progresses through the university can be very
 rewarding.
     Education is not always a dynamic, exciting,
 intellectually satisfying experience for all students,
 however. Somehow educators have succeeded in
 quieting the ever inquisitive mind of the young child.
 We have removed the spark from many learning
 experiences. Students often approach their studies
 with something less than enthusiasm. Although
 financial rewards are present for those who complete
 college and university study, I feel that the student is
 not sufficiently encouraged to find self satisfaction in
 the use of his or her mind. The solution of a difficult
 engineering problem should afford the student a
 degree of intellectual accomplishment. I make no
 claim that this good feeling will necessarily generate
 as much excitement as a date, or success in an
 athletic endeavor, but I do feel that some degree of
 self satisfaction must be present. If it is not, the
 student should seek a career in some field other than
 engineering. As an educator, I have sought ways that
 can help the individual student develop enthusiasm
 for his chosen profession and the courses of study
 that comprise his formal education.
    In developing my courses I have tried to in-
corporate the following observations into their
structure:

a. The contemporary student has literally been
   bombarded by various means of visual com-
   munication. In particular, the impact of movies
   and television on the student's learning habits
   cannot be overlooked.
b. Conventional lecture methods are inherently
  inefficient in their use of available time.
c. By and large students are rather poor note takers.
  While serving in this secretarial role their primary
  intellectual effort is directed to reproducing the
  material that the professor writes on the black-
  board. Classes can no longer serve as the vehicle
  to transfer material from the notes of the professor
  to the notes of the student without going through
  the mind of either one.

     These considerations led me to conclude that
new approaches were needed in classroom teaching
efforts. In preparing for the core thermodynamics
course, ES-8, I tried to develop an educational at-
mosphere that would utilize rather than be frustrated
by the three observations cited above. Conventional
lecture methods do have some definite drawbacks
not the least of which is the limitation that they
impose in the amount of information that can be
transferred in a given period of time. I prepared
slides containing the basic definitions, concepts and


equations of the subject matter. These slides serve as
the skeleton of the course.
     Several requirements for the slides were ob-
 vious. The slides had to be concise, readable and
 furthermore be interesting enough in their own right
 so the viewer would not quickly become bored with
 them. The "text" material on a given slide is
 superimposed on a colorful background and a
 colored slide is prepared from them. At the very
 least these slides do make the act of staying alert and
 attentive in lecture easier.
     Just as "Man doth not live by bread alone",
 engineering students have not really mastered a
 given subject matter until they can demonstrate
 problem solving skills in the subject matter. The use
 of the slides does free some of the lecture time to
 pursue this activity. At the present time we rely more
 on the individual attention given to the student in the
 recitation portions of the course to achieve these
 skills. Recitations, like little girls, come in all
 wrappings, however. Some are very very good and
 some are horrid! Recently I have attempted to
 correct this problem by making a series of SELF
 STUDY EXAMPLES available to all students in the
 course. These SELF STUDY EXAMPLES contain a
 problem statement followed by a listing of the
 educational objectives that are appropriate for that
 problem, finally followed by a very detailed solution
 to the problem. My work in developing the SELF
 STUDY EXAMPLES is unfinished at the present
 time. I ultimately will include a series of SELF
 STUDY    EXAMPLES    that will require  some
 calculations on the student's part. Furthermore, I
 plan to prepare a series of cassette tapes that not
 only elaborate on some of the steps of the various
 problems but also ask questions that will enable the
 student to evaluate whether he or she has grasped
the appropriate concepts. Finally a series of tests will


SKYSCRAPER ENGINEER_WINTER, 1971






















