be included within the SELF STUDY EXAMPLES. I
have been very encouraged with the students' initial
use of the SELF STUDY EXAMPLES. Over 50 per
cent of a class of 35 students made A grades on the
first examination this term and that is truly ex-
ceptional experience in my classes. When the
materials are all developed, I visualize their use in
the following manner. The student goes to a facility
similar to the present language lab and works with
the tapes and SELF STUDY EXAMPLES ap-
propriate for that period of study. A competent
graduate assistant and /or professor will be available
to provide additional guidance and direction. I see
no reason why a very bright or conscientious student
could not complete all SELF STUDY EXAMPLES
and internal tests before the normal end of the term.
Under these circumstances he or she could ask to
take a final exam and could complete the course by
passing that exam.
     As I review my educational procedures I am
constantly striving for means to economize on the
transfer of information. Audio-visual materials have
shown promise and I'll no doubt continue to explore
their use.
     It is important that I do not develop an
educational approach that totally divorces the
student from the professor, for that would be a grave
error. We are all members of a society whose
common good can only be improved through mutual
trust and understanding. In a sense developing this
understanding is really the number one educational
objective of any of my courses.
    Yes, we must help the student to realize that the
society he or she is about to enter is a highly complex
one and that an ability to solve academic problems in
engineering courses is only one of a number of skills
that will be vital to them. I feel that if we fail to help


the student develop an increased awareness of
himself, his fellow man and the role they will play in
guiding our planet in the immediate future that we
have educated only part of the man or woman.
    I cannot too strongly encourage any student to
avail themselves of the unique opportunities present
at this university. Perhaps at no other time of their
lives will students be able to select from such a
cosmopolitan   menu  of lectures, recitals, art
exhibitions, and the like. Equally important are the
opportunities to discover other individuals who
having come from a spectrum of ethnic backgrounds
can provide great stimulus. Question your ideals and
those of the society in which you live. Become active
in political groups and the groups such as GASP. If
you do involve yourself not only will your time spent
at the university be more satisfying to you but you
will also be laying a solid foundation for satisfaction
in your post baccalaureate careers.
     In summary, your education must be the
simultaneous development of your technical skills
and understanding of yourself and your fellow man.
In our contemporary world this last point cannot be
too strongly emphasized. These feelings were ex-
pressed by one of the true geniuses of all time, Albert
Einstein. Paul Ehrenfest, a contemporary of Ein-
stein, had written to him in one of Ehrenfest's
distressed moments complaining that he could not
do the most original physics. Einstein's answer was
the following:
"You are complaining about yourself again,
and are dissatisfied with yourself. Just think
how little difference it will make in twenty
years how one has loitered about on this earth,
just so long as one has done nothing base.

