THE CONSCIENCE

     In today's technological society, the engineer is
a very important man. Our whole life style has been
formed by the inventions of the engineer. The
engineer made possible the industrial growth of the
last century, creating the economy which our society
has grown accustomed to.
    Engineers could turn this nation into a "Garden
of Eden." We could reverse and prevent further
pollution  of the   environment. By  increasing
technological application, we could reduce the
working hours of the entire labor force. We could
design adequate housing and efficient transportation
for the cities. There are an infinite number of
problems which engineers could solve to raise the
quality of life in America.
    Engineers still have a choice in these matters.
We can refuse to work on any project that we do not
approve of. One engineer who refuses to work on a


new bomb has done more to end the war than a host
of protesters.
     A precedent was established at the Nuremberg
War Crimes Trial: "Obedience to government is no
excuse for committing crimes against humanity." In
other words, the chemical engineer who creates na-
palm in Dow's factories is as guilty as the Army
general who orders a village burned.
    The conscience of the engineer who works on a
defense project which he feels is wrong, should
prevent him from working on that project. By
refusing to work on national projects which he feels
are irrelevant or detrimental to humanity, the
engineer can do his part to change the way things
are.
    Guns and bullets are designed by engineers. If
engineers would refuse to fabricate weapons, the
foot soldier could not fire them. As human beings,
our consciences should stop us from using our skills
to destroy life when we could be saving it.


