       By: THOMAS E. GESTRICH
                        and
               GARY D. BROWN


 INTRODUCTION
     Today, in the United States, an estimated 55,000 individuals die
 each year of kidney failure. Of these, approximately 20 per cent could
 have an extended lifetime of seven years using present dialysis
 technology at an annual cost of $12,000 /person.1 Due to this high cost,
 kidney dialysis is inaccessible to the public. The number of deaths could
 be sharply reduced by increasing the availability of dialysis equipment
 with particular emphasis on reduced cost. Also, due to the side effects of
 uremic poisoning from transient dialysis, a portable lifetime dialysis unit
 operating continuously would extend the average lifetime as well as
 being psychologically less straining on the patient.

 ABSTRACT
     The design of an ultrafiltration system to process 500 cc/min of
 plasma producing 150 cc/min of plasma water is described. The system
 is based on the Amicon Corporation UM-1 membrane which is synthetic
 and non-cellulosic. The membrane is supported on a tough polyolifin
 frame which is non-toxic to proteins and inert to blood. Five square feet
 of membrane is contained in a stack of five one foot square membranes
 contained in a 9 x 9 x 4 inch package. Provisions are made for conducting
 plasma between the membrane and collecting the filtrate. An additional
 0.4 atmosphere pressure drop across the membrane surface is made
 available by suction obtained from a specially designed filtrate pump.
 Power requirement of the system is estimated to be approximately 3
 watts. The system is overdesigned by 30 cc/ min of filtrate over the
 normal flowrate of a healthy glomerular system. The membrane
 specificity is almost identical to that of a healthy glomerulus. The flow
 rates are manually controlled.

 KIDNEY FUNCTION
    The functions the natural kidney performs and how these functions
are related to the physiology of other organs systems is important in
understanding the requirements which an artificial kidney must meet.
    In maintaining constancy of the internal environment, the kidney
performs several functions:9



32


             MACHINE




     1. Water balance - if an excess of water is ingested the kidney
     compensates by producing large quantities of dilute urine. If
     water intake is deficient, the kidney will attempt to compensate
     by a decrease in urine volume and an increase in urine con-
     centration. However, a minimum quantity of urine (3000400 ml
     day) must be excreted to rid the body of nitrogenous wastes.
     Thus, renal capacity for water balance must be made up by the
     mechanisms of thirst and increased intake.
     2. Electrolyte balance - the kidney regulates the con-
     centration of ions such as sodium, potassium, calcium,
     phosphate, bicarbonate and sulfate within narrow limits despite
     large variations in food intake and metabolic activity.
     3. Acid-base balance -    most of the end products of
     metabolism are acidic in nature. The kidney handles this acid
     load by the excretion of acid radicals. In addition, ammonia is
     secreted into the tubular urine, where it forms ammonium ion
     and thus removes hydrogen ions.
     4. Waste excretion -    the nitrogenous end products of
     protein metabolism, such as urea and creatinine, are excreted
     by the kidneys. In the processing of those waste products, other
     substances such as glucose and amino acids must be selectively
     reabsorbed so that they will be conserved by the body.
     5. Hormone and enzyme synthesis - the kidney appears to be
     a source for at least two hormones. Renin is an enzyme
     produced in the renal cortical juxtaglomerular cells; it exerts
     effects upon extracellular volume and  blood  pressure.
     Erythropietin is the hormone that regulates rate of red blood
     cell production by the bone marrow.

HYPERFILTRATION
    The first step in urine formation is production of an ultrafiltrate of
plasma by glomerular filtration. In ultrafiltration large molecules such as
plasma proteins and lipids are sieved out but small molecular weights are
passed. Thus, tubular urine is protein free and contains all of the


