crystalloids present in plasma in the same concentrations as the plasma
except for small differences due to the Donnan equilibrium.4
     The filtration process requires expenditure of energy to overcome
 the frictional resistance of the membrane and to perform the osmotic
 work of separating protein from the plasma. The relationship among the
 various pressures is shown in the following equation with approximate
 values of pressures available in man shown below.

                             Pf = Pg - (Pos + Pc)

           Pf = filtration pressure = 25 mm Hg
           Pg = glomerular pressure = 70 mm Hg
           Pos = osmotic pressure = 30 mm Hg
           Pc = Intracapsular Hydrostatic Pressure = 15 mm Hg


TUBULAR REABSORPTION
    Plasma constituents, such as glucose are known to be filterable at
the glomerulus but do not appear to any extent in excreted urine.
Therefore, reabsorption of the substances from the tubular urine must
occur.9
                          Proximal Tubule
    Reabsorption of salt and water is isomotic and occurs by the
following process:8
     1. sodium is active reabsorbed.
     2. water is passively reabsorbed by the osmotic force created by
active reabsorption of sodium ions and the passive diffusion of chloride
ions.
    3. chloride is passively reabsorbed down the electrochemical
gradient created by sodium reabsorption.
    4. four-fifth to seven-eights of the glomerular filtrate is normally
reabsorbed in the proximal tubule.
     5. essentially all glucose reabsorption and secretion occurs in the
proximal tubule.
                            Distal Tubule
     One-fifth to one-eight of the water in the glomerular filtrate is
reabsorbed here. Water permeability of the tubular epithelium is a
function of the presence of antidiuretic hormone. Variable amounts of
sodium are reabsorbed. The reabsorbed sodium is exchanged with H+
and K+ which are secreted in this zone.
                Renal Regulation of Acid-Base Balance
     Metabolism produces an excess of acid substances. The chief acid
product' is CO2 which is volatile and expelled to the lungs. Oxidation of
proteins producs large quantities of non-volatile acids such as sulfuric
and phosphoric. To maintain neutrality of the body fluids, the excess
acid is excreted in the urine.
     When excreted the acid anions must carry with them      a
stoichiometric amount of salts (Na+, K+, Ca++). The amount of base
which a milliequivalent of acid will carry with it in the urine depends
