II. MATERIAL OF CONSTRUCTION (3)
     The relation between composition of artificial surfaces and their
ability to initiate hemostatic processes has been under much speculation.
One fact is established, glass, the universal containing material for
mematological studies is among the more active surfaces. This activity
can be reduced by coating it with various hydropholic materials such as
thin films of silicones. A crucial factor in any attempt to access surfaces
is knowing what blood actually confronts; in all cases proteins are
quickly absorbed on artificial surfaces and the initial reactions are
complex.
     The greatest advance is the development of nonthrombogenic
surfaces in heparin, which when previously attached to surfaces in
contact with blood prevented clotting. In spite of the fact that herarin is
widely recognized as an effective anticoagulant in solution, its mode of
action in the absorbed state remains puzzling.




34


      The factors causing adhesion of platelets (clotting) are poorly
  understood. Platelet physiology is complex and difficult to study in part
  because platelets are very small cells with high environmental sensitivity.
  An ideally nonthrombogenic surface will not accumulate cells or
  coagulated proteins, shorten cell lifetimes, accelerate the turnover of
  clotting proteins or accelerate or retard normal hemostasis.
      Present artificial organs are prevented from inducing coagulation
  reactions by injecting large doses of heparin into the blood which
  prevents completion of the clotting reaction.13
      In the absence of a clear criterion for selecting materials on the
  basis of their nonthrombogenicity, the design guidelines which can be
  offered to minimize coagulation reactions in artificial kidneys pertain to
  flow conditions. Stagnation appears undesirable; blood left in contact
  with artificial surfaces for long periods even when heparinized may tend
  to clot, turbulence with substantial recirculation of the same blood,
  appears to result in the deposition of tendrils. Since emboli are serious
  threats to the patient, returning blood is passed through a filter.6
      Design practice dictates the avoidance of stagnation and the use of
 smooth non-porous materials in the construction of artificial organs.
 Surface areas exposed to blood should be no greater than required.
      Materials in contact with the blood should not leak or corrode so as
 to release foreign or toxic materials into the blood. Trace quantities of
 metal may be toxic; many plastics contain additives which can be
 released upon extended soaking in warm ionic solutions. Blood and ionic
 solutions are highly corrosive to most metals and may promote stress
 cracking of many plastics.
     In general, there is less clotting activity on the high pressure side of
 the heart. Therefore the design should include coupling to this side.

 III. CONCENTRATION POLARIZATION (11)
     When a fluid moves directly through any filter that retains dissolved
 and suspended substances an enriched layer or film accumulates on the
 surface of the filter, interferring with access bulk of the fluid to the
 actual filter surface. If this is allowed to consolidate, a secondary
 membrane is formed. This tendency to accumulate retained species at
 the membrane's surface is a phenomenon called concentration
 polarization. It will, if not counteracted, ultimately lead to formation of a
 gel layer that resist passage of the solvent and species to which the
 membrane is permeable. During fractionation of mixes macromolecules
 by membranes it is found that accumulation of the larger species on the
 membrane surface interferes with access of the smaller species, creating
 the appearance that the membrane is not permeable to the smaller
 species. This can, however, be effectively minimized by appropriate
 equipment design. The task of the designer is to maximize return of the
 concentrated macrosolute from the membrane surface to the bulk of the
 liquid. The challenge is to take fullest advantage of the extraordinary
 transport capabilities of the anisotropic membrane by keeping its surface
 as free of accumulations as possible. The simplest means of reducing the
 boundary layer is turbulent mixing by mechanical agitation of the fluid
 close to the membrane suface.11 Another effective means of managing
 the concentration polarization problem is to propel the fluid over the
 surface of the membrane in very shallow channels (o.010-0.030 inch)
 producing smooth laminar flow at relatively high velocity.

