aflo UM-1 are presented in Table III. For comparison, some transport
properties of the glomerular membrane and cellophane are also in-
cluded. The UM-1 membrane is more retentive and less water permeable
than the glomerular membrane (70-100 A) of the human kidney. The
inferiority of cellophane membranes with respect to water permeability
is clearly evident.
     The clearance characteristics of the U-1 membrane are shown in
Figure C. The sharp cutoff characteristics of the UM-1 membrane are
readily visible. This data was extracted from a laboratory study
simulating blood flow.
    This membrane has been shown to be highly compatible with blood.
Proteins do not absorb on the membrane nor are they denatured by
contact with the membrane. The polyelectrolyte complex resin from
which this membrane is produced has also been shown to be non-
thrombogenic in contact with the blood in vivo. These attributes add to
the membrane's desireability for blood purification.
    The system has been designed to maintain a 400 mm  g pressure
drop across the membrane. The design value of.03 cm3/cm  should be
adequate. Values of .05 cm3/cm2min have been obtained during batch
testing, but due to concentration polarizations (mainly proteins), the flux
is generally lower.


