  The fastest changing elements of our society over
the last five to ten years have been our priorities. At
the recent meeting with the student body, Dean
Hoelscher stated that the School of Engineering
must change with the changing priorities.
  When Sputnik hurtled around the world in 1957,
the leaders of the nation decided that we must beat
the Russians to wherever they were going. If we were
to beat the Russians, we needed engineering
superiority. At that time, most of the top engineers in
each field came from about 20 top colleges in the
country. The plan was implemented to build ad-
ditional centers of excellence at existing schools.
Through many departments of the government,
money was funnelled into engineering and science
schools. From  the gleeming new   edifices of
education poured highly competent technocrats.
These graduates were highly sought and well paid
through the sixties in research, seventy per cent of
which was financed by the government. The
research supported our space program and war
effort in Southeast Asia. War machinery and space
hardware required much more engineering talent
than consumer goods and products for social im-
provement. The increased production of top quality
engineers was created and   used by the im-
plementation of the post-Sputnik priorities.
    By the end of the sixties, we began reaping the
bitter fruits produced by social neglect and in-
ternational irresponsibility. Beginning with Watts,
social convulsions of frustration spontaneously
erupted and raged in the rotting cores of our inner
cities. Our nation, sick of the war crimes we commit
daily in Asia, and the waste of American lives, now
wants out of Vietnam (73 per cent in a recent poll).
The people no longer grasp the esoteric reasons for
continuing the space program when our cities, the
nucleii of our society, are becoming more inoperable
because of their long-term low priority status.
    The priorities have changed, if only in the wants
of the people. They want out of the war in Southeast


Asia now. They want to stop wasting exorbitant
amounts of money on the space program. The
people's representatives, as usual, are hard of
hearing. We don't know from day to day what
country our President is going to have us invading
next and the statesmen representing the aerospace
industry have invented another money-disposal
system, the SST.
    How can the School of Engineering at Pitt
respond responsibly to the will of the people and to
the needs of the struggling city of Pittsburgh?
Because our Engineering School is one of the new
centers of excellence, not many of the graduates of
center city schools such as Schenley, Fifth Avenue,
and Westinghouse, are academically competent to
matriculate at the School of Engineering. We are
providing  bigger and  better things for the
academically well-groomed progeny of the great
white noose, while taking up more taxable land and
rendering it untaxable. To cease to be a leech on our
troubled  city, I suggest that the  School of
Engineering should lessen the rigor of its courses,
lower its admission requirements, and thus make
possible the admission of more center city high
school graduates.
    The creative development for the priorities of
the seventies has already been done. Prototypes
already exist for planned communities, mass transit,
pollution control, and health care. Less rigorously
trained engineering graduates would more than
suffice to produce and implement the tools for social
improvement. The School of Engineering would, at
the same time, be helping to end the cycle of poverty
in the inner city, while dispelling the aspect of a
hopeless future for many young men and women of
Pittsburgh. Pittsburgh doesn't need another Carnegie
Mellon; it needs a school to educate and serve its
residents. Our nation  doesn't need  another
engineering marvel. It needs rebuilt and restructured
communities, good mass transit, universal health
care, a cleaned-up environment and good education
for the masses.


